Until a definition of developing countries is agreed, data under this indicator provisionally aggregates all countries located in ""developing regions"" for the purposes of monitoring ""developing countries""." In common practice, Japan in Asia, Canada and the United States in northern America, Australia and New Zealand in Oceania, and Europe are considered ""developed"" regions or areas. Until a definition of developing countries is agreed, data under this indicator provisionally aggregates all countries located in ""developing regions"" for the purposes of monitoring ""developing countries""."
